This paper deals with the construction of Voronoi diagrams, which is a fundamental problem in computational geometry. The paper specifically focuses on the farthest-segment Voronoi diagram, which is a variant of the Voronoi diagram where the distance metric is defined in terms of line segments. This falls under the category of computational geometry (cs.CG). 

The paper also deals with Davenport-Schinzel sequences, which are a type of combinatorial object that arise in computational geometry and other areas of computer science. This falls under the category of data structures and algorithms (cs.DS). 

The paper presents an algorithm that has an expected linear-time complexity, which involves probabilistic analysis. This falls under the category of discrete mathematics (cs.DM). 

The paper also deals with the complexity of the Voronoi diagram, which is a measure of the number of regions and edges in the diagram. This falls under the category of computational geometry (cs.CG) and graph theory (cs.GR).
